1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,700
So, let's start with a somewhat provocative question: what if one of the greatest

2
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:10,160
inventions in history, the plow, were actually at the root of some of the

3
00:00:10,160 --> 00:00:13,660
inequalities between men and women that we still see today?

4
00:00:13,660 --> 00:00:16,160
It sounds like a strong idea, right?

5
00:00:16,160 --> 00:00:21,140
Well, in this analysis of ours, we will follow the traces of a truly extraordinary research to

6
00:00:21,140 --> 00:00:24,039
see if there is any truth to this hypothesis.

7
00:00:24,039 --> 00:00:29,219
Let's start with a real enigma of our time: why do opinions

8
00:00:29,219 --> 00:00:33,979
on the role of women in the world still vary so much today? And we're not talking about small

9
00:00:33,979 --> 00:00:39,340
nuances—the differences are sometimes abyssal, almost like from one planet to another.

10
00:00:39,340 --> 00:00:44,700
Let's look at a concrete example that comes straight from the data of one of the research sources:

11
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:49,500
Question: when jobs are scarce, should men have more right to a job

12
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:50,500
than women?

13
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:51,980
Listen to the answers.

14
00:00:51,980 --> 00:00:57,060
In Iceland, only 3.6% agree, practically no one.

15
00:00:57,060 --> 00:01:05,260
Now, let's move to Egypt: almost 95% of the population gives that same answer—95%! But

16
00:01:05,260 --> 00:01:07,460
how is such a massive difference possible?

17
00:01:07,460 --> 00:01:12,900
Well, incredibly, the answer could be hidden in a very old tool, and here

18
00:01:12,900 --> 00:01:17,859
it is—our main suspect. A group of economists—we're talking about Alberto

19
00:01:17,859 --> 00:01:24,180
Alesina, Paola Giuliano, and Nathan Nunn—pointed their finger right at it: the plow.

20
00:01:24,180 --> 00:01:28,260
Wait, not today's high-tech plow, but the traditional one, the one

21
00:01:28,260 --> 00:01:31,580
used in agricultural societies centuries and centuries ago.

22
00:01:31,580 --> 00:01:36,060
To tell the truth, the idea didn't come out of nowhere; it's based on a hypothesis by a Danish

23
00:01:36,060 --> 00:01:41,600
economist, Ester Boserup. Imagine, as early as 1970, she had suggested that gender

24
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:46,500
roles as we know them today could be rooted right there, in the different ways

25
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:48,660
of farming in the distant past.

26
00:01:48,660 --> 00:01:52,020
Okay, let's try to visualize the difference.

27
00:01:52,019 --> 00:01:56,739
On one hand, we have farming done with a hoe; it requires less physical strength, you can

28
00:01:56,739 --> 00:02:01,780
stop and start easily—in short, it's work compatible with childcare.

29
00:02:01,780 --> 00:02:05,299
Men and women could participate there more or less equally.

30
00:02:05,299 --> 00:02:08,699
Then the plow arrives, and here, well, everything changes.

31
00:02:08,699 --> 00:02:13,379
The plow requires significant physical strength, especially in the upper body, and then

32
00:02:13,379 --> 00:02:18,300
you have to manage draft animals—impossible to do while looking after small children. And it's

33
00:02:18,300 --> 00:02:23,939
here that an almost natural specialization for the time is born: men in the fields, women

34
00:02:23,939 --> 00:02:24,939
at home.

35
00:02:24,939 --> 00:02:30,060
And this is the key point, the real crux of the matter: what at the beginning was

36
00:02:30,060 --> 00:02:34,939
only a practical division of tasks, over time, turned into a

37
00:02:34,939 --> 00:02:38,300
proper cultural norm—it took root.

38
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:43,780
The idea that a woman's natural place was in the home didn't just fall from the sky, but was

39
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:47,300
born, according to this theory, precisely from a technology.

40
00:02:47,700 --> 00:02:52,700
Okay, so far it's a fascinating theory, but we need proof, right? So let's go and see

41
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:54,700
what historical data tells us.

42
00:02:54,700 --> 00:03:00,300
Well, the researchers did an amazing job; they analyzed data on hundreds of

43
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:05,100
pre-industrial societies, and the results, well, are clear-cut, very clear.

44
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:09,460
In societies that used the plow, women's participation in agricultural work

45
00:03:09,460 --> 00:03:10,460
plummeted.

46
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:15,939
In all phases, from sowing to harvest—basically, more plow equals fewer women

47
00:03:15,939 --> 00:03:18,539
in the fields, an almost mathematical link.

48
00:03:18,539 --> 00:03:24,699
But wait, because there's a piece of data that is even more surprising, almost shocking, I'd say:

49
00:03:24,699 --> 00:03:30,180
the use of the plow is linked to a 1.3% decrease in the ratio between the height of

50
00:03:30,180 --> 00:03:31,900
women and that of men.

51
00:03:31,900 --> 00:03:32,900
And what does that mean?

52
00:03:32,900 --> 00:03:37,060
Well, adult height depends a lot on how you were fed as a child, so

53
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:41,780
this data suggests that, in those societies, less was invested in girls compared

54
00:03:41,780 --> 00:03:42,780
to boys.

55
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:46,699
A physical, objective indicator of the different perceived value.

56
00:03:46,699 --> 00:03:51,939
Okay, that's the past, but the real question—the one that interests us most—is:

57
00:03:51,939 --> 00:03:56,699
How is it possible that an ancient technology can still have such a strong

58
00:03:56,699 --> 00:03:57,699
influence today?

59
00:03:57,699 --> 00:04:01,300
Well, apparently the legacy is very clear and can be measured.

60
00:04:01,300 --> 00:04:05,979
Data tells us that countries where ancestors used the plow still tend today to

61
00:04:05,979 --> 00:04:11,340
have fewer women in the workforce, fewer female-led businesses, and fewer women in politics.

62
00:04:11,340 --> 00:04:16,180
The correlation is truly impressive, it's immediately obvious, and to understand how

63
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:18,740
strong this effect is, think about this:

64
00:04:18,740 --> 00:04:23,980
Just a small difference in the historical use of the plow is enough to find today nearly

65
00:04:23,980 --> 00:04:27,340
seven percent less female labor participation.

66
00:04:27,340 --> 00:04:32,540
It's a massive impact that has survived centuries of economic, social, and

67
00:04:32,540 --> 00:04:33,540
technological changes.

68
00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:36,459
And here we get to the heart of the matter.

69
00:04:36,459 --> 00:04:40,220
Okay, the correlation is there, but what does it depend on?

70
00:04:40,220 --> 00:04:46,340
Is it the fault of cultural beliefs passed from father to son, mother to daughter, or

71
00:04:46,340 --> 00:04:52,900
is it that the use of the plow created, over time, laws and institutions that still disadvantage

72
00:04:52,900 --> 00:04:53,900
women today?

73
00:04:53,900 --> 00:04:57,340
The problem is, how do you separate the two things?

74
00:04:57,340 --> 00:05:00,420
Isolating the effect of culture is extremely difficult.

75
00:05:00,420 --> 00:05:05,900
If we compare, say, Italy and Sweden, we are comparing everything—different laws,

76
00:05:05,900 --> 00:05:08,780
different labor markets, different histories.

77
00:05:08,780 --> 00:05:13,580
How can we be sure that it's culture that makes the difference and not everything

78
00:05:13,580 --> 00:05:14,580
else?

79
00:05:14,580 --> 00:05:17,140
And this is where the study becomes brilliant.

80
00:05:17,140 --> 00:05:21,900
To solve this puzzle, the researchers had an idea: look at second-generation

81
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:26,260
immigrants, for example in the United States or in Europe.

82
00:05:26,260 --> 00:05:27,780
Let's think about it for a moment.

83
00:05:27,780 --> 00:05:32,780
These people were born and raised in the same country; they have the same laws, the same

84
00:05:32,780 --> 00:05:35,500
job opportunities, the same schools.

85
00:05:35,500 --> 00:05:40,540
The only real major difference between them is the culture they inherited from their parents

86
00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:41,939
and their country of origin.

87
00:05:41,939 --> 00:05:45,620
The basic concept is simple but powerful.

88
00:05:45,620 --> 00:05:52,120
Institutions and laws are fixed in a country, but culture—culture travels with

89
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:53,120
people.

90
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:55,620
They carry it with them like invisible baggage.

91
00:05:55,620 --> 00:06:02,259
And the result is the ultimate proof: even in this natural laboratory, the effect of the

92
00:06:02,259 --> 00:06:03,259
plow persists.

93
00:06:03,259 --> 00:06:08,099
Women whose parents come from countries with a strong plow tradition are

94
00:06:08,099 --> 00:06:13,379
less likely to work, even if they were born and raised in a completely

95
00:06:13,379 --> 00:06:14,379
different context.

96
00:06:14,379 --> 00:06:20,019
This tells us one thing: it's culture itself, transmitted within the family, that makes the difference.

97
00:06:20,019 --> 00:06:25,899
So, let's wrap things up: what's the final verdict on this ancient tool?

98
00:06:25,899 --> 00:06:29,899
What does this incredible chain of evidence teach us?

99
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:33,820
Let's go back to the initial question: did the plow create patriarchy?

100
00:06:33,820 --> 00:06:39,180
Well, the answer isn't a flat 'yes'—that would be too simple. Not on its own, obviously,

101
00:06:39,180 --> 00:06:43,780
but this research shows us, in a rather convincing way, that it was a very powerful

102
00:06:43,780 --> 00:06:44,780
historical force.

103
00:06:44,780 --> 00:06:49,980
It shaped beliefs about gender roles so deep that, incredibly, they have reached

104
00:06:49,980 --> 00:06:50,980
us today.

105
00:06:50,980 --> 00:06:53,780
But then, how much does this cultural heritage weigh?

106
00:06:53,780 --> 00:06:59,860
The researchers tried to estimate it: culture alone explains between 12 and 43

107
00:06:59,860 --> 00:07:02,460
percent of the total effect of the plow.

108
00:07:02,460 --> 00:07:03,460
And the rest?

109
00:07:03,460 --> 00:07:08,660
The rest are other factors, like laws or the economy, but wait—even these factors

110
00:07:08,660 --> 00:07:13,300
were, in turn, influenced by that division of labor born thousands

111
00:07:13,300 --> 00:07:14,300
of years ago.

112
00:07:14,300 --> 00:07:15,300
It's all connected.

113
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:21,699
And all this leaves us with one final question, perhaps the most important one: if such an ancient

114
00:07:21,699 --> 00:07:27,939
technology has left such a deep mark, what are the invisible plows of

115
00:07:27,939 --> 00:07:28,939
today?

116
00:07:28,939 --> 00:07:35,699
What are the technologies, habits, and events that are shaping at this very moment

117
00:07:35,699 --> 00:07:40,180
the cultural norms and the society of tomorrow, perhaps without us even noticing?